      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The massive political pushback stems from a fundamental disconnect between abstract economic models and the lived experiences of voters, who are often focused on immediate concerns like job security and cultural preservation. Populist movements successfully frame immigration as a zero-sum game, suggesting that any gain for one group must mean a direct loss for the native working class. This narrative is politically potent because it taps into deep-seated anxieties about national identity and economic fairness, regardless of complex econometric findings.",
      "source": "target",
